# Explainable LLaVA-Rad: Bayesian Evaluation Pipeline

This repository contains the official code and evaluation pipeline for the Bachelor's thesis evaluating the clinical explainability and hallucination rates of **LLaVA-Rad**, a multimodal large language model for chest X-ray interpretation.

Instead of relying on basic n-gram metrics (like BLEU/ROUGE), this pipeline utilizes **RadGraph** to extract clinical entities and relations, applying a **Bayesian Latent Variable Model (PyMC)** to calculate a structurally grounded Explainability Score ($E_i$).

## 🗂️ Repository Structure

```text
.
├── code/
│   └── scripts/               # Data preparation and subset building scripts
├── data/
│   ├── lists/                 # Filtered image filenames (e.g., 1500 subset)
│   └── queries/               # JSON configuration for inference queries
├── notebooks_v2/              # Core evaluation pipeline (Jupyter Notebooks)
│   ├── 01_validate_pilot.ipynb
│   ├── 02_align_subset_to_inference.ipynb
│   ├── 03_run_radgraph_extraction_from_aligned_input.ipynb
│   ├── 04_analyze_radgraph_results.ipynb
│   └── 05_pymc_explainability_model_A.ipynb (and other variants)
├── outputs/                   # Processed Bayesian models, CSVs, and diagnostics
└── README.md

Note on external data: The images, refs and large output directories are ignored via .gitignore. The MIMIC-CXR dataset requires credentialed access via PhysioNet. The underlying LLaVA-Rad repository and weights are also fetched independently to avoid Git submodule conflicts.

⚙️ Setup & Installation
Due to the heavy computational requirements of LLaVA-Rad, a dedicated GPU environment (e.g., RunPod with RTX 3090 / 4090 / A6000) is highly recommended.

1. Clone this Repository
2. Setup External LLaVA-Rad Repository
This project relies on the official LLaVA-Rad architecture for the inference step. Clone it directly into the code directory (it is git-ignored by this repository to keep the repository clean).

3. Environment & Dependencies
Create a virtual environment and install both the LLaVA-Rad requirements and the Bayesian evaluation stack:

🚀 Execution Pipeline
The workflow strictly enforces a modular separation of concerns.

Stage 1: Data Preparation
Identify the necessary chest X-ray images based on the structured query subsets (e.g., 1500 cases).

Stage 2: Model Inference (LLaVA-Rad)
Execute the generative model to produce raw clinical findings. You must have the MIMIC-CXR-JPG dataset downloaded and placed in mimic-cxr-jpg.

Stage 3-6: Evaluation & Bayesian Modeling
Once the raw inference file is generated, the remainder of the pipeline is executed sequentially via the provided Jupyter Notebooks in notebooks_v2.

01_validate_pilot.ipynb: Initial validation of the extracted queries.
02_align_subset_to_inference.ipynb: Aligns study IDs, drops empty text outputs, and handles data conservation.
03_run_radgraph_extraction_from_aligned_input.ipynb: Transforms the paired texts (Reference vs. Generated) into structured clinical graphs.
04_analyze_radgraph_results.ipynb: Computes precision, recall, and mismatch rates between the generated and reference reports.
05_pymc_explainability_model_A.ipynb & variations: The core contribution. Runs the PyMC MCMC sampler to derive the latent explainability score (
E
i
E 
i
​
 ) and conducts downstream regressions against hallucination burden. Contains robust checks like R-hat and Posterior Predictive Checks (PPC).
 
📊 Results & Diagnostics
All final outputs, including highest-density intervals (HDI), MCMC trace plots, zero-divergence checks, and maximum R-hat metrics (ensuring model convergence 
≤
1.02
≤1.02), are automatically saved to the respective folders in the outputs/ or outputs_v2 directory when running the PyMC notebooks.

